		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper13</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>Layout-Sensitive Generalized Parsing</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/SebastianErdweg.html">Sebastian Erdweg</a>, <a href="../profile/TillmannRendel.html">Tillmann Rendel</a>, <a href="../profile/ChristianKästner.html">Christian Kästner</a>, <a href="../profile/KlausOstermann.html">Klaus Ostermann</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_14">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_14</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s main result is a generalized parsing technique/tooling that handles layout-sensitive syntax systematically.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> Layout sensitivity is treated in a way that supports combining grammars and languages without losing compositionality.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The work extends grammar-based specification techniques for defining syntaxes that include layout constraints.
</li></ul></li></ul>
